  "text": "The OpenJDK HotSpot JIT compilation pipeline is defined through several key C++ components located in src/hotspot/share/. The CompileBroker class (src/hotspot/share/compiler/compileBroker.hpp) is the central broker that manages all compilation requests and coordinates the compilation workflow. CompilerThread (src/hotspot/share/compiler/compilerThread.hpp) represents the dedicated threads that execute compilation tasks. AbstractCompiler (src/hotspot/share/compiler/abstractCompiler.hpp) is the base class that defines the common interface for all compiler implementations. The JIT compilation pipeline consists of two primary tiers: C1, the client (first-tier) compiler defined in src/hotspot/share/c1/c1_Compiler.hpp with the Compiler class, provides quick compilation with moderate optimizations suitable for short-lived applications; and C2 (also called Opto), the optimizing (second-tier) compiler defined in src/hotspot/share/opto/c2compiler.hpp with the C2Compiler class, provides aggressive optimizations for long-running hot methods. Both C1 and C2 compilers inherit from AbstractCompiler, allowing the CompileBroker to manage them uniformly through a common interface. This architecture enables HotSpot's tiered compilation strategy where methods can be progressively compiled from interpreted bytecode to C1 and then to C2 based on execution frequency and profiling data."
}

